Gapminder

For this assignment, we are going to use data from gapminder. Gapminder includes information about economics, population, social issues, and life expectancy from countries all over the world. We will use three data sets, so please load all three.

One thing to note is that the data include years beyond 2021. These are projections based on modeling done by the gapminder organization. Start by importing the data.

  1. (2 points) Lets limit the data to the past 100 years (1920-2020). For these years, which country has the highest life expectancy? How about the lowest life expectancy?

life_expecancy_tidy %>%

  group_by(country) %>%

  1. (3 points) Although we can see which country has the highest life expectancy for the past 100 years, we dont know which countries have changed the most. What are the top 5 countries that have experienced the biggest improvement in life expectancy between 1920-2020?
life_expecancy_tidy %>% 
  filter(year >= "1920" & year <= "2020") %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarize(min_life_exp=min(life_expectancy_col),
            max_life_exp=max(life_expectancy_col)) %>% 
  mutate(delta= max_life_exp-min_life_exp) %>% 
  top_n(5, delta) %>% 
  arrange(desc(delta))

  filter(country=="Kazakhstan") %>% 
  group_by(year, country) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=life_expectancy_col, group=country, color=country))+
  geom_line()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(hjust=0.25)) +
  labs(title = "Biggest Improvement in Life Expectancy",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Life Expectancy (Age)",
       fill = "Country")+

  scale_color_trek("romulan")

According to Wikipedia, the large dip in life expectancy during the early 1930s was due to what was called the Kazakh famine, or the Goloshchyokin Genocide. This was a time in which much of Kazakhstans livestock and grain were confiscated to feed the cities, resulting in the deaths of 1.5-2.3 million people. Around 650,000 Kazakhs fled the country to avoid the famine. According to the Borgen Project, life expectancy has been able to improve due to transitioning from lower-middle-income to upper-middle-income status in less than 2 decades. Another factor was immigration back into the country as well.

The large dip in per person GDP during the early 1980s is due to the 1979 energy crisis, which was caused by the Iranian Revolution. Oil prices shot up from 1979-1980, causing the larger buying countries to increase their interest rates to control the inflation. High interest rates and high unemployment rates both contributed to the economic contraction that is shown in the countries on the graph. This information was sourced from Wikipedia.
